20 ARTICLE 20.5. PROGRAMS ADMINISTERED BY THE
21 STATE
22 Chapter 1. Educational Service Centers
23 Sec. 1. As used in this chapter, "applicable nonpublic school"
24 refers to a nonpublic school that has one (1) or more employees.
25 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "board" refers to the board of an
26 educational service center described in section 8 of this chapter.
27 Sec. 3. (a) As used in this chapter, "educational service center"
28 means an extended agency of school corporations, charter schools,
29 and applicable nonpublic schools that:
30 (1) operates under rules established by the state board;
31 (2) is the administrative and operational unit that serves a
32 definitive geographical boundary, which, to the extent
33 possible, must be aligned with the boundary of a regional
34 works council's region established under IC 20-19-6 (before
35 its expiration); and
36 (3) allows school corporations, charter schools, and applicable
37 nonpublic schools to voluntarily cooperate and share
38 programs and services that the school corporations, charter
39 schools, and applicable nonpublic schools cannot individually
40 provide but collectively may implement.
41 (b) Programs and services collectively implemented through an
42 educational service center may include, but are not limited to, the
EH 1004—LS 6983/DI 110

44
1 following:
2 (1) Curriculum development.
3 (2) Pupil personnel and special education services.
4 (3) In-service education.
5 (4) State-federal liaison services.
6 (5) Instructional materials and multimedia services.
7 (6) Career and technical education.
8 (7) Purchasing and financial management.
9 (8) Needs assessment.
10 (9) Computer use.
11 (10) Research and development.
12 Sec. 4. The state board may provide for the establishment of and
13 procedures for the operation of educational service centers.
14 Sec. 5. (a) The state board shall do the following:
15 (1) Adopt a comprehensive plan to implement this chapter.
16 (2) Determine the areas in Indiana that will be served by an
17 educational service center.
18 (b) In determining the geographic area to be served by an
19 educational service center, the state board shall consider the
20 following:
21 (1) Physical factors.
22 (2) Socio-economic factors.
23 (3) Educational factors.
24 (4) Existing cooperative efforts and agreements.
25 Sec. 6. An educational service center must be established under
26 rules adopted by the state board to develop, provide, and make
27 available to participating schools, including participating charter
28 schools and applicable nonpublic schools, those services requested
29 by the participating school corporations, participating charter
30 schools, and applicable nonpublic schools and approved by the
31 state board.
32 Sec. 7. Educational service centers shall be located throughout
33 Indiana to allow each school corporation, charter school, and
34 applicable nonpublic school to have an opportunity to:
35 (1) be served by; and
36 (2) participate in;
37 an approved center on a voluntary basis by resolution of the
38 governing body of the school corporation, by the approval of an
39 organizer of a charter school, or by the approval of the governing
40 board or entity of an applicable nonpublic school.
41 Sec. 8. An educational service center shall be governed in its
42 local administration by a board selected by an assembly comprised
EH 1004—LS 6983/DI 110

45
1 of the:
2 (1) superintendent or the superintendent's designee from each
3 participating school corporation;
4 (2) organizer of a charter school or the organizer's designee
5 from each participating charter school; and
6 (3) chief administrative officer of an applicable nonpublic
7 school or the chief administrative officer's designee.
8 Sec. 9. (a) The state board shall adopt uniform rules to provide
9 for the local selection, appointment, and continuity of membership
10 for boards.
11 (b) Vacancies on a board shall be filled by appointment by the
12 remaining members of the board.
13 (c) Members of a board serve without compensation.
14 Sec. 10. A board may employ the following:
15 (1) An executive director for the educational service center.
16 (2) Other personnel the board considers necessary to:
17 (A) carry out the functions of the educational service
18 center; and
19 (B) do and perform all things the board considers proper
20 for successful operation of the center.
21 Sec. 11. (a) Any funds, including donated funds and funds from
22 federal or other local sources, shall be used to pay for the costs of
23 establishing or operating an educational service center.
24 (b) An educational service center may administer programs and
25 funds from any of the sources described in subsection (a). All
26 activities funded from federal sources must follow all applicable
27 federal guidelines, rules, and regulations.
28 Sec. 12. This chapter does not prohibit an educational service
29 center from receiving and using matching funds from federal
30 sources in any amount for which the educational service center
31 may be eligible.
32 Chapter 2. Teacher Referral System
33 Sec. 1. As used in this chapter, "referral system" refers to the
34 teacher employment opportunities referral system established by
35 section 2 of this chapter.
36 Sec. 2. The department shall establish and keep current a
37 computerized teacher employment opportunities referral system.
38 Sec. 3. The referral system must:
39 (1) be capable of identifying the available public school
40 teaching positions within Indiana;
41 (2) provide the pertinent information on individuals who are
42 seeking employment as teachers; and
EH 1004—LS 6983/DI 110

46
1 (3) be accessible to school corporations, teachers, prospective
2 teachers, and state educational institutions.
3 Chapter 3. Teacher of the Year
4 Sec. 1. A teacher of the year may be invited to serve one (1) year
5 of professional leave with:
6 (1) an Indiana postsecondary educational institution; or
7 (2) the department.
8 Sec. 2. (a) The school where a teacher of the year is regularly
9 employed shall do the following:
10 (1) Grant the teacher a one (1) year professional leave to
11 provide service as described in section 1 of this chapter.
12 (2) Allow the teacher to return to the school from the
13 professional leave:
14 (A) to the same or a comparable position as the teacher
15 held before the professional leave; and
16 (B) without loss of accrued benefits or seniority.
17 (3) Continue to provide the teacher all benefits of employment
18 with the school other than salary.
19 (b) The department shall reimburse a school for the cost of
20 benefits provided by the school to a teacher under subsection
21 (a)(3).
22 Sec. 3. If a teacher of the year provides service for the
23 department or an Indiana postsecondary educational institution
24 under this chapter, the department or the Indiana postsecondary
25 educational institution shall pay the teacher's salary for the term
26 of the service and shall reimburse the teacher's regular employer
27 for the teacher's benefits during the term of service.
28 Chapter 4. Curricular Materials
29 Sec. 1. (a) Not later than July 1, 2027, and each July 1
30 thereafter, the department shall evaluate, approve, and publish a
31 list of high quality curricular materials for use in the following
32 subjects:
33 (1) Science.
34 (2) Technology.
35 (3) Engineering.
36 (4) Math.
37 (5) English/language arts.
38 The department shall post the list approved under this subsection
39 on the department's website.
40 (b) Subject to subsection (g), the department shall:
41 (1) determine the:
42 (A) process for evaluating and approving curricular
EH 1004—LS 6983/DI 110

47
1 materials under subsection (a); and
2 (B) requirements for curricular materials to be approved
3 and included on the list described in subsection (a); and
4 (2) collaborate with teachers in evaluating and approving high
5 quality curricular materials in English/language arts under
6 subsection (a).
7 (c) The department shall publish an annual report that
8 describes the method used to conduct the evaluation required
9 under subsection (a) and that contains the results of the evaluation.
10 The report must do the following:
11 (1) Provide a list of each curricular material evaluated and a
12 summary of the evaluation for each curricular material.
13 (2) Provide a listing and summary review for the high quality
14 curricular materials approved by the department.
15 (3) Include any clarification or response from the publisher of
16 a curricular material related to the department's summary
17 review provided under subdivision (2).
18 (4) Include the written, exact, and standard statewide price
19 provided by the publisher of the curricular material under
20 subsection (e) for each high quality curricular material
21 approved by the department under this section.
22 (d) A governing body and superintendent may use the list
23 approved under subsection (a) in complying with IC 20-26-12-24.
24 (e) Before the department may approve curricular material for
25 inclusion on the list under subsection (a), the publisher of the
26 curricular material must:
27 (1) provide the department a written, exact, and standard
28 statewide price for each curricular material; and
29 (2) enter into a data share agreement with the department in
30 the manner prescribed by the department.
31 (f) A publisher may request that an update to the publisher's
32 curricular materials and corresponding prices replace the
33 information on the curricular materials set forth in the report
34 under subsection (c).
35 (g) At a minimum, the process for evaluating curricular
36 materials and the requirements for curricular materials to be
37 approved and included on the list described in subsection (a) must
38 include the following:
39 (1) The availability and use of benchmark, formative, interim,
40 or similar assessments to identify students that require
41 remediation or enrichment and provide individualized
42 instruction.
EH 1004—LS 6983/DI 110

48
1 (2) The incorporation of experiential learning opportunities.
2 (3) An evaluation of the benchmark, formative, interim, or
3 similar assessment data provided by the publisher of the
4 curricular material pursuant to the data share agreement
5 described in subsection (e).
6 (4) The alignment of the curricular material to Indiana's
7 academic standards developed by the department under
8 IC 20-31-3-2.
9 (5) The age appropriateness of the content.
10 Sec. 2. (a) The secretary of education shall notify the governing
