15 Chapter 20. Science of Reading Grant
16 Sec. 1. As used in this chapter, "charter school" has the meaning
17 set forth in IC 20-24-1-4.
18 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "elementary school" means a
19 public elementary school, including a charter school.
20 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "grant" refers to a grant
21 awarded under section 7 of this chapter.
22 Sec. 4. (a) This subsection applies before July 1, 2027. As used
23 in this chapter, "literacy coach" refers to an individual whose
24 primary responsibility is to provide literacy training and support
25 to administrators and teachers. This subsection expires July 1,
26 2027.
27 (b) This subsection applies after June 30, 2027. As used in this
28 chapter, "literacy coach" means an individual:
29 (1) whose primary responsibility is to provide literacy
30 training and support to administrators and teachers; and
31 (2) who has received the literacy endorsement described in
32 IC 20-28-5-19.7.
33 Sec. 5. A literacy coach shall prioritize the following:
34 (1) Modeling effective instructional strategies for teachers.
35 (2) Facilitating study groups.
36 (3) Training teachers in:
37 (A) data analysis; and
38 (B) using data to differentiate instruction.
39 (4) Coaching and mentoring colleagues.
40 (5) Working with teachers to ensure that evidence based
41 reading programs, which include:
42 (A) comprehensive core reading programs;
EH 1004—LS 6983/DI 110

83
1 (B) supplemental reading programs; and
2 (C) comprehensive intervention reading programs;
3 are implemented with fidelity.
4 (6) Training teachers to diagnose and address a reading
5 deficiency.
6 (7) Working with teachers in applying evidence based reading
7 strategies in other content areas, including:
8 (A) prioritizing time spent on those teachers;
9 (B) activities and roles that will have the greatest impact
10 on student achievement; and
11 (C) prioritizing coaching and mentoring in classrooms.
12 (8) Helping to increase instructional density to meet the needs
13 of all students.
14 (9) Working with students through:
15 (A) whole and small group instruction; or
16 (B) tutoring;
17 in the context of modeling and coaching in or outside of a
18 teacher's classroom.
19 Sec. 6. Money allocated for grants under this chapter must be
20 used for the following:
21 (1) Placing literacy coaches in elementary schools for the
22 purposes of training and supporting teachers and
23 administrators in order to improve instruction related to the
24 science of reading.
25 (2) Training teachers and school principals in instructional
26 practices aligned with the science of reading.
27 (3) Increasing instructional time, including summer literacy
28 programs or high-dosage tutoring, for students who have been
29 identified as struggling readers based on a diagnostic
30 screening authorized by the department under IC 20-35.5-2-2.
31 (4) Elementary schools and school corporations purchasing
32 curricular materials that:
33 (A) align with science of reading; and
34 (B) receive approval by the department.
35 (5) Covering costs for teachers to obtain a literacy
36 endorsement described in IC 20-28-5-19.7.
37 Sec. 7. (a) Subject to section 8 of this chapter, the department
38 may award a grant under this chapter to a school corporation or
39 charter school that does the following:
40 (1) Applies for a grant on a form provided by the department.
41 (2) Submits a detailed description of a plan that:
42 (A) must include:
EH 1004—LS 6983/DI 110

84
1 (i) placing literacy coaches in elementary schools for the
2 purposes of training and supporting teachers and
3 administrators in order to improve instruction related to
4 the science of reading; and
5 (ii) training teachers and school principals in
6 instructional practices aligned with the science of
7 reading; and
8 (B) may include, if the school corporation or charter school
9 is requesting grant funds for the purpose described in
